column168: ON DECEMBER 14, 1998, AT APPROXIMATELY 19:35 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, LOADED WITH METHYL ETHYL KETONE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A LOOSE MANWAY COVER (DOME LID) WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS'S PITTSBURG, KANSAS RAIL YARD.  THE TANK CAR LEAKED ONLY WHEN THE LADING WAS SLOUCHING FROM MOVEMENT.  THEREFORE, THE TANK CARE WAS THEN ISOLATED TO A NON-ACTIVE TRACK TO PREVENT FURTHER POSSIBLE MOVEMENT AND FURTHER POTENTIAL SPILLAGE.  ALL REQUIRED NOTIFICATIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY CONDUCTED BY KSC PERSONNEL.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED KCS PERSONNEL TO TIGHTEN THE MANWAY COVER.  THE MANWAY COVERED TIGHTENED, FIXING THE LEAK, AT 0745 HOURS ON 12/15/98.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.
DETERIORATED STORAGE TANK DELIVERY CAUSED RUSTED BOTTOM OF TANK TO FAIL.  RELEASED PRODUCT CONTAINED ON CONCRETE BASEMENT FLOOR.

column168: PASSENGERS BOARDED TWA AIRCRAFT ORIGINATING IN SAN FRANCISCO, FLIGHT 208 ON DECEMBER 6TH WITH A CONNECTION TO FLIGHT 603 IN ST.LOUIS WITH FINAL DESTINATION OF OKLAHOMA CITY. THE TWO ITEMS, ONE WOODEN BOX AND A PLASTIC-TYPE COOLER,WERE LEFT UNCLAIMED IN THE AREA OF TWA. TWA AGENT WENT TO PLACE THE ITEMS IN A SECURE AREA AND WAS OVERCOME WITH FUMES FROM THE WOODEN BOX. AIRPORT POLICE AND FIRE COMPANY WERE NOTIFIED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESCUE SQUARD CLOSED THE ENTIRE BAGGAGE CLAIM AREA, WHICH AFFECTED TWA,AMERICAN AND NORTHWEST AIRLINES. THE FAA WERE ALSO NOTIFIED. DESCRIPTION OF ITEMS ARE ON ATTACHED SHEET. CONSISTENT WITH TWA POLICY, PASSENGERS WERE QUESTIONED ON NON-BAGGAGE ITEMS AT CHECK-IN SAN FRANCISCO.POLICE CONTACTED MANAGER OF WOOD DESIGNS AND HE DID COME TO THE AIRPORT. TWA CONSIDERS THIS A UNDECLARED GOODS INCIDENT.

LIDE THEN OBTAINED THE BILL AND WENT TO OFFICE TO CHECK THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK WHILE I STAYED ON THE DOCK TO KEEP THE FREIGHT SECURE.  ONCE THE ERG BOOK WAS CHECKED LIDE THEN CALLED OUR CHEMICAL SPILL RESPONSE TEAM IN DOTHAN, AND SPOKE WITH JOY.  THIS WAS 02:45 OCLOCK.  WHEN THEN FOLLOWED HER INSTRUCTIONS.  PUT ON SAFETY EQUIPMENT, RUBBER GLOVES PROTECTIVE MASKS AND CLEANED UP THE LITTLE THAT WAS SPILLED, TAPED UP THE BUSTED BAG AND SENT THE SHIPMENT TO FINAL DESTINATION.

A DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD UPON ARRIVING AT THE FACILITY AND DISCOVERED THAT THE LID OF A 16 GALLON DRUM CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM TO SPILL INTO THE SPILL INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER ABSORBED THE LIQUIDS AND PLACED THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER  FOR SHIPMENT. THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 200 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DR. SE, HEBRON, OH 43025 FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO CHECK LID RETAINING RINGS TO ENSURE THEY ARE SECURE PRIOR TO MOVING LOADS.

A WAREHOUSEMAN DROPPED A FIVE GALLON CONTAINER OF WASTE WHILE MOVING IT IN THE WAREHOUSE.  THIS CAUSED THE LID TO POP OFF RESULTING IN A SPILL OF ONE AND A HALF GALLONS OF WASTE.  THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH PADS THAT WERE PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK.  THE LID WAS REPLACED ON THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 15 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET, DOLTON, IL 60419 FOR RECYCLING.  THE WAREHOUSEMAN WAS COUNSELED TO EXERCISE MORE CARE WHEN MOVING CONTAINERS WITH THE WAREHOUSE.

column168: A DOCK WORKER UNLOADING DRUMS FROM A STORAGE TRAILER DISCOVERED ONE THAT HAD LEAKED ABOUT ONE QUART OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM DUE TO MISSING GASKET AROUND THE LID.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SCRAPED UP AND PUT BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND THE MISSING GASKET WAS REPLACED.  THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY TWO POUNDS OF WASTE THAT ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD, SMITHFIELD, KY 40068 FOR RECYCLING.  DRIVERS WERE COUNSELED TO ENSURE THEY PLACE DRUM SEALS ON DRUMS WHEN THEY LOAD THEM TO PREVENT SIMILAR OCCURRENCES IN THE FUTURE.

DRS ARRIVED BACK TO SERVICE CENTER AND OPENED TRAILER AND SAW DRUM LEAKING.  PALLET JACK HAD SLID ACROSS TRAILER FLOOR AND PUNCTURED SIDE OF DRUM TOWARDS BOTTOM.  NOT MUCH RELEASE OF MATERIAL AT THIS TIME.  WE MOVED DRUM OUT OF TRAILER TO PREVENT LEAKING FURTHER INTO TRAILER AND ONTO OTHER DRUMS.  DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING AND THEN OVERPACK WAS PLACED ON TOP, DRUM TURNED TO WHERE IT WAS FULLY CONTAINED IN OVERPACK.  ALL ABSORBENT WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND SEALED, TO RETURN TO SHIPPER. INCIDENT WILL BE DISCUSSED WITH DRS AND IT WILL BE COVERED FULLY IN OUR NEXT SAFETY TAILGATE MEETING.

column168: NO PIPING ON THE CARGO TANK, NOR DID THE CARGO TANK LEAK.  THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING DOWN A TWO-LANE RURAL ROAD.  A DEER RAN OUT IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER STEERED THE TRUCK SHARPLY TO THE LEFT TO AVOID HITTING THE DEER.  THE FRONT WHEEL THEN HIT A POT HOLE IN THE PAVEMENT.  THIS CAUSED A LOSS OF CONTROL BY THE DRIVER, AND THE TRUCK LEFT THE ROAD. TRUCK TURNED OVER IN A FIELD AND LAID ON ITS SIDE.  THE IMPACT OF THE TRUCK'S CARGO TANK IMPACTING THE GROUND, JARRED THE 80% OUTAGE GAUGE OPEN ON THE CARGO TANK.  THIS OPENING IS PROTECTED BY A NUMBER SIZE 54 OUTAGE ORIFICE, SO LEAKING WAS MINIMAL (2 GALLONS).  OUTAGE GAUGE OPENING VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND LEAKING STOPPED.

ON 12/18/98 AT 9:30 AM A DRIVER BROUGHT IT TO MY ATTENTION THAT WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER THAT THERE WAS A DRUM LEAKING. WHEN I WENT TO INVESTIGATE HE ALSO INFORMED ME THAT HE COULD NOT TELL THAT IT WAS LEAKING UNTIL HE KICKED THE DRUM BACK ON THE DRUM DOLLY.  THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE WELDED SEAM ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  I THEN TOLD ALL DRIVERS TO LEAVE THE LOCATION UNTIL I NOTIFIED MY SAFETY SUPERVISOR.  I THEN PROCEEDED TO CALL CHIP MCLENDON WITH CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  I THEN FOLLOWED HIS INSTRUCTIONS.  I ALSO CALLED CHEMTREC, HM RELEASE HOTLINE, RODNEY MYERS (LOCAL MANAGER), AND OEP.  I ALSO FOLLOWED THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. LAFAYETTE H/M TEAM-A RESPONDED AND THEY PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column168: ON DEC. 2, 1998 A 20FT SEALAND OF BAGGED DRY ACTIVE WASTE WAS SHIPPED BY GTS DURATEK'S SPECIALIZED GENERATOR SERVICES DEPARTMENT FROM ICF KAISER IN TONAWANDA, NY.  THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A TOLL BOOTH ON EXIT 58 OFF I-90 WEST WHEN HE NOTICED LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE SEALAND DOOR ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE LIQUID RAN OFF THE FLATBED INTO THE GRAVEL AND HE THEN PLACED A TRASH CAN UNDER THE DRIP THAT WAS COMING OFF OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY DUTY OFFICER AT GTS DURATEK AND THEN PERSONNEL AT ICF KAISER WERE NOTIFIED.  SINCE THE ICF KAISER PERSONNEL WERE CLOSER THAN THE SAMPLING OF THE AFFECTED AREA WAS PERFORMED AND NO CONTAMINATION WAS FOUND.  SEE THE ATTACHED LAB REPORTS ON THE MATERIAL SAMPLED.  THE LOAD WAS THEN BROUGHT BACK TO ICF KAISER WHERE THE DOORS WERE OPENED AND THE LIQUID THAT PLASTIC BAGS LOADED INTO THE SEALAND.  THE SEALAND CONTAINER WAS DESIGNED TO HOLD DRY MATERIALS AND THE CONDENSATION FROM THE OUTSIDE OF THE PLASTIC BAG LEAKED OUT THE SEAL OF THE SEALAND.

ON THE MORNING OF DECEMBER 14,  THE SPILL CLEAN UP AGENT WAS NOTIFIED OF A PACKAGE ACCEPTED FROM TRAVIS AFB THAT WAS NOW STAINED WITH WHAT APPEARED TO BE A FUEL SPILL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE.  THE SPILL CLEANUP AGENT FOUND AN AIRCRAFT PART THAT HAD NOT BEEN CLEANED AND DRIED.  THE BOX WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND THERE WAS NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT.  AFTER BEING CALLED BY THE CCR FEDEX STATION.  I CONTACTED THE FAA ABOUT THIS UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  THE FAA INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT AND RELEASED IT TO BE HELD AT THE FEDEX STATION TO BE PICKED UP BY THE SHIPPER.

THIS BROKEN COLOGNE BOTTLE OF THE BODY SHOP COLOGNE WAS FOUND IN A PAPER ENVELOPE.  THIS MAY HAVE BEEN THE INNER CONTENTS OF A PACKAGE. THE OTHER PACKAGE WAS NOT FOUND. DURING THE AFTERNOON SORT AT THE FEDEX MEMPHIS SORT CENTER.  THIS PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT.  THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER PROPERLY CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND STORED IT IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  SINCE THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED OVER A LONG HOLIDAY WEEKEND.  THE SHIPPER'S COMPANY WAS CONTACTED, BUT THE SHIPPER WAS NOT AVAILABLE.  THIS PACKAGE IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN A SECURED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BUILDING PENDING THE SHIPPER'S CALL WITH DISPOSITION INFORMATION.

ON DECEMBER 19, 1998, AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS A RAILROAD TANK CAR, NUMBER GATX 54669, LOADED WITH CYCLOHEXANE, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS BEAUMONT, TEXAS RAIL YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO THE NORTH END OF TRACK #5 AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  ALL REQUIRED LOCAL, STATE & FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE IMMEDIATELY PERFORMED BY KCS.  AS A PRECAUTION, LOCAL AUTHORITIES CLOSED 0.25 MILE PORTION OF MARTIN LUTHER KING PKWY AND APPROXIMATELY 1 CITY BLOCK OF WASHINGTON STREET.  THE SHIPPER'S RESPONSE CREW REPAIRED THE DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT 1830 HOURS THAT SAME DAY.  LOCAL OFFICIALS SUBSEQUENTLY OPENED ALL STREETS AT 2100 HOURS. THE SHIPPERS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR DECONTAMINATED THE AFFECTED AREAS AS REQUIRED BY THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED ON THE WEST WALL INCOMPATIBLE BELT.  ONE OF ONE PAINT CAN HAD A LID THAT CAME LOOSE, EVEN THOUGH IT HAD CLIPS THE LEAK WAS DUE TO INSUFFICIENT INNER PACKAGING.  THE CAN AND THE REMAINDER OF THE CONTENTS WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM TO BE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON AND SPILLED CONTENTS WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: DURING UNLOAD OPERATIONS IN LAS, THIS DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DROPPED DURING HANDLING. CONTENTS WERE CLEANED UP AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER THE NEXT DAY.

APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR AFTER BEING LOADED ON AN AIRCRAFT PALLET, WHILE LOADING FOR AN INCOMING FLIGHT, THE ABOVE MENTIONED PACKAGE WAS LOADED AND LEAKING.  WHEN THE LEAKING WAS NOTICED THERE WAS NO ACTIVITY (FORKLIFTS ETC) IN THE AREA.  THE PC HAD BEEN STORED ON THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE FOR ABOUT AN HOUR.  THE FAA, CHICAGO FIRE DEPT, HAZ MAT TEAM WERE NOTIFIED ALONG WITH OTHER AUTHORITIES. (POLICE/DOA ETC).  THE BUILDING WAS COMPLETELY EVACUATED, BY THE HAZMAT TEAM. WHEN THE BUILDING WAS RE-OPENED CLEAN HARBOURS (CHI) CLEANED THE CONTAMINATED AREAS.  10 EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  THE PACKAGING FAILURE IS UNDER INVESTIGATION BUT NO SIGNS OF STRESS WERE FOUND ON THE PACKAGE, THAT WOULD CAUSE THE SPILL. THE REST OF THE CONSIGNMENT IS IN FRANKFURT AND IS BEING HELD FOR INVESTIGATION BY LUFTHANSA AND THE GERMAN LBA (FAA).  THIS WAS DONE AFTER IS WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INCORRECT PACKAGE WAS USED (NOT ALLOWED).  COMBINATION PACKAGING SHOULD HAVE BEEN USED. SINGLE WAS USED.

AIRCRAFT TURBINE ENGINE PART LEAKED JET FUEL FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM.  LEAK APPEARS TO HAVE COME FROM THE INNER UNIT AND FUEL LINES.  PACKAGE IS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO HAVE FALLEN TO THE FLOOR AND LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND SPILL CLEANUP TEAM WAS NOTIFIED.  IT WAS DISCOVERED DURING THEIR INVESTIGATION THAT ONE OF THE INNER GLASS BOTTLES HAD BEEN BROKEN.  THE GLASS HAD BEEN PROTECTED BY STYROFOAM, BUT IT TOO HAD CRACKED.  CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED TO ASK FOR A DISPOSITION.

PACKAGE WAS BEING UNLOADED FROM A CONTAINER AT THE INPUT WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE SMOKING.  PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED AND THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED.  I WAS AVAILABLE AS AN ON-CALL PERSON, AND RESPONDED ALSO.  THE PACKAGE WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE OTHERS, AND ISOLATED TO PREVENT THEM FROM POSSIBLY CATCHING FIRE.  ONE OF THE MANAGERS IN THE AREA USED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO TRY TO PUT OUT THE SMOKING PACKAGE.  AS THE PACKAGE WAS CONTINUING TO SMOKE I NOTICED THE NAME DATREX  ON A PACKAGING LABEL, AND QUICKLY DETERMINED THIS WAS PROBABLY A MAN-OVER BOARD DEVICE.  I MOVED PEOPLE FURTHER AWAY, SINCE A PREVIOUS INCIDENT INVOLVING DATREX HAD DISCHARGED ALSO.  THE PACKAGE FINALLY FINISHED SMOKING AFTER ABOUT 30 MINUTES, AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THERE WAS A SECOND PACKAGE TO THIS SHIPMENT AND I  WENT TO THE OUTBOUND AREA TO SEARCH FOR IT.  THE SECOND PACKAGE, AIRBILL NUMBER 8077-4735-2617, WAS FOUND AND HELD FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THIS SECOND BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY LABELS, MARKINGS, NOR DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH IT.  ALEX EVANS WITH THE BNA/CASFO WAS CONTACTED, AND ANDREW JOHNSON WAS SENT TO INVESTIGATE. THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE BOTH CONTACTED AND THE PACKAGE IS STILL BEING HELD UNTIL INVESTIGATION IS COMPLETED.

The msds was requested to get more information on this spilled material. Information from the manufacturer classified this as a corrosive material. I notified the FAA and the package was held pending FAA investigation. There were no hazardous markings or labelings and no dangerous goods paper work was presented to fedex.

Responded to package using proper PPE and decision tree. Used no label response sheet.The spill had a ph of 0. Went to corrosive response sheet. Neutralized the spill with sodium bicarbonate and absorbed with clay absorbent. Disposed of using UPS procedure.

The salvage drum package was delivered to the recipient since eleven of the inner bottles were undamaged.

Package was damaged during the sorting operation by a lift scale. The package fell underneath the scale and was crushed. The spill clean up team was notified and they placed the package into a salvage drum and contacted the shipper for disposition.

This package was observed damaged during the sorting operation. The package fell from a baggage cart and was struck by the wheel of another vehicle. The spill clean up team was notified and they inspected the package and placed the contents into a salvage drum. The shipper was later contacted for a disposition on this package.

Package was damaged during the sorting operation when this package fell from a baggage cart and was struck by the wheel of the following baggage cart. The package was isolated and the spill clean up team was notified. The package and its contents were placed into a salvage drum, and the shipper was later contacted regarding disposition.

Package was discovered leaking during the outbound package sorting operation. This package fell from a baggage cart and was struck by the wheel of the trailing baggage cart. The spill clean up team was notified and placed the damaged package inside a salvage drum. The shipper was contacted regarding the incident to seek a disposition for the damaged contents. Most of the spill was contained inside the packaging.

At approximately 12:30 a.m., 12/18/98 while switch crew was handling UtLX 99094 ld. ammonia anhydrous in Madison, IL terminal railroad switch  yard to spot at consignee unloading facility, they noted an ammonia odor and reported same. Inspection of car revealed that there was a small vapor release from the area of the outage ball type angle valve with ice build up around the valve created by vapor release. Chem-trek notified at 1:10 a.m. on 12/18/98, who in turn had a representative from LaRouch Industries contact TRRA representative. It was decided to place a wet (water) rag on the area of vapor release to control the release as best as possible and then place the car in consignee's facility for repairs to the area of the vapor release and future unloading of product as normal. At time of repairs by LaRoche representatives, cause of release was determined to be caused by a loose outage valve allowing vapor release. Defect corrected by LaRoche representative.

column168: This box was found to have a stain and odor associated with it during the sorting operation. When the package was noticed, it was isolated and the spill clean up team was notified. Upon their inspection of the box and its contents, it was noticed that a bottle label stated that it was a flammable product and to read the MSDS. The shipper was called to inform them of the leakage and they faxed a copy of the material safety data sheet. The MSDS stated that this product had a 25 degree farenheit flash point. The outer box did not have any labels, markings or dangerous goods declaration paperwork with the shipment. Package was held and Andrew Johnson of the FAA, MEM office was notified so that he could begin an investigation.

This package was found during the inbound sort operation at the Londonderry fedex ramp facility. The outside of the box was stained with a fuel like material. The spill clean up agent placed the stained package in a drum and called dangerous goods administration. The box had no dangerous goods markings or labels and there was no shipper's declaration for dangerous goods offered to Fedex. I contacted the FAA and the package was held pending their investigation.

Package was discovered leaking during the package sorting operation at this facility. The outer package did not have any labels, markings or any dangerous goods declaration paper work traveling with this shipment. The shipment was noticed due to the strong odor and stain associated with the package. The package was isolated and the spill clean up person was notified. Upon his inspection, it was suspected that the contents of this package might be considered as dangerous goods. The FAA was contacted and Fred Kaufeld of the DEN/CASFO was to investigate. The shipper was contacted and advised that this package was under investigation.

This package was damaged during the sorting operation at this facility. The package was observed to have fallen and was struck by other packages. A strong odor was noticed and the spill clean up person was notified. The package was quickly isolated to a well ventilated area due to the odor. The package was contained in a salvage drum and I was notified. The box had not been labeled, marked, or declared as containing dangerous goods but due to the strong odor it was suspected. I notified the shipper of the incident and requested some product information. The material safety data sheet was faxed to me. The flash point on the MSDS stated that the product was 21 degrees farenheit. I contacted Jim Berk with the ORD/CASFO of the incident. He was to investigate the incident.

column168: AIR PRODUCTS TRAILER 613037 WAS EMPTY AND RETURNING TO ITS HOME TERMINAL. WHEN THE DRIVER OBSERVED THAT THE INNER VESSEL WA BUILDING PRESSURE. THE DRIVERS ADVISED THEIR SUPERVISOR THAT THE  PRSSURE WAS BUILDING AND THEY WERE ADVISED TO FIND A SAFE LOCATION AND TO SAFELY VENT  OFF THE PRESURE WHICH THEY DID SAFELY. THE PRESSURE WAS STABOLIZED AND THE UNIT WAS TAKEN TO NEW ORLEANS LA FOR INSPECTION. column168: THE TRACTOR/ TRAILER WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGULAR VEHICLE ACCIDENT RESULTING IN A ROLLOVER. column168: On December 18, 1998, at approximately 4:30 a.m., a Montana Refining Company (MRC) product delivery truck and trailer, loaded with diesel fuel skidded off of Highway 200 during a blizzard. The truck overturned on its top in the borrow ditch and the trailer turned on its side. The incident occurred approximately one mile west from the top of Rodgers Pass in Lewis and Clark county, MT. The product truck and trailer was loaded with 9,052 gallons of #2 low sulfur diesel fuel. Two small leaks were discovered in the product delivery truck fuel storage compartment. The leaks were plugged by MRC responders using a combination of wooden stakes and beeswax. Approximately 191 gallons of diesel fuel leaked from the product truck before it was plugged. MRC responded immediately to the incident by dispatching the Company's oil spill response team, five towing trucks, two empty fuel trucks, and two vacuum trucks. The response consisted of two task forces. Task force one was instructed to recover the product from the truck and trailer and then remove the equipment from the site. Task force two was instructed to contain and recover all spilled diesel fuel. Task Force one recovered 9301 gallons of diesel fuel from the truck and trailer and returned the product to the Great Falls refinery that evening. The truck and trailer were recovered and towed to repair shops in Missoula later in the day. Task Force two deployed 50 feet of containment boom and 30 feet of absorbent spaghetti below the incident area. All of the spilled diesel fuel was trapped above the sand dike placed by the Highway Department to prevent migration of the product down the borrow ditch. (Figure I). MRC responders used vacuum trucks to recover the water and fuel trapped behind the impoundment. Small pockets of product were cleaned up using absorbent blankets. The spent absorbent, water and product were taken to the refinery for recovery and disposal. The entire incident was declared over at 3:45 p.m. on 12/18/98. Approximately 191 gallons of diesel fuel spilled onto the ground. (Table 1). Most of the product was recovered using vacuum trucks and absorbent blankets. MRC anticipates a few gallons (probably <5 gallons) was trapped under ice or entrained in the snow. MRC does not feel that this small amount will endanger the environment.

column168: DUE TO ICY ROAD CONDITIONS, AN ACCIDENT OCCURRED. THE ACCIDENT CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE PUMP FITTING ON A TANK TRAILER CAUSING 38,000 POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT TO RELEASE. HANSER'S WRECKER COMPANY OF BILLING, MONTANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS ON SCENE. THE FREE PRODUCT EVAPORATED AND NO FURTHER REMEDIATION WAS REQUIRED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AN EDWARD OIL COMPANY TANK WAGON DRIVER WAS DELIVERING #2 HIGH-SULFUR FUEL OIL WHEN THE AIR ELIMINATOR FROZE, CAUSING OIL TO BLOW BACK INTO THE BACK OF THE TANK WAGON, WHERE IT DRAINED ONTO THE SNOW ON THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT. THE CONTAMINATED SNOW WAS SHOVELED UP AND PLACED INTO BARRELS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE BALANCE WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL DRY AND RAGS AND WERE PLACED INTO THE WASTE DISPOSAL BARRELS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: UPON UNLOADING IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE TOTE HAD A VALVE THAT THE PRODUCT FROZE IN. THE VALVE EXPANDED DUE TO THE FROZEN PRODUCT. THE VALVE CRACKED AND THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK OUT OF VALVE.

TRAILER SLID OFF ROAD INTO CATTLE GUARD POST WHILE UNIT WAS NEGOTIATING AN ICY CORNER ON OIL FIELD ROAD. THE POST HIT AND PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. IT SETS UP LIKE PARAFFIN WAX AND WAS PICKED UP WITH A TRACK HOE. CONTAMINATED PRODUCT AND SOIL WAS DISPOSED OF BY CAP ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES DURING GENERAL CLEAN UP OF THE TANK BATTERY.

column168: AT THE TIME OF THE CARRIERS VEHICLE ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION, A CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEE ADVISED THE DRIVER OF MATERIAL RUNNING FROM THE TRAILER.  DRIVER USED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO PREVENT H/M FROM ENTERING A STORM SEWER.   CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO EFFECT CLEANUP.

INTER LINE CARRIER REFUSED ONE PALLET OF BAGS OF SOLID H/M DUE TO APPARENT PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  VEHICLE REDIRECT TO CONTRACTOR'S FACILITY.   CONTRACTOR BROKE DOWN PALLET, IDENTIFIED, REMOVED, SECURED AND RETAINED THREE TORN BAGS.  CONTRACTOR DECONTAMINATED CARRIER'S TRAILER; RESTACK THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT ONTO ITS PALLET FOR DELIVERY.

PAIL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT CARRIER'S FACILITY.  IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET THAT IT WAS ON AND SECURED.  ITS BOTTOM CHIME APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN SUBJECTED TO CRUSHING FORCE DURING LOADING OR IN TRANSIT.  OVERPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

DURING UNLOADING AT CARRIER'S FACILITY, A DOCK WORKER OBSERVED SOME LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, ON THE TOP OF ONE DRUM AND ON SOME OTHER FREIGHT.  CAUSE WAS DETERMINED TO BE LEAKAGE THROUGH A CLOSURE SEAL.  FAULTY DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.  THE OTHER FREIGHT WAS DECONTAMINATED AND DELIVERED.
A CRACK DEVELOPED IN THE TRAILER WHILE TRANSPORTING PRODUCT TO CUSTOMER. METAL FATIGUE. TRAILER HAS BEEN REPAIRED.
SINGLE DRUM ON A PALLET TIPPED, PUNCTURING ONE DRUM & DENTING ANOTHER. RECOMMENDATION TO IMPROVE FREIGHT SEANREMENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 6:20 AM ON DECEMBER 30, 1998, WHILE TRAVELING NORTH ON INTERSTATE 81 NEAR LICKDALE, PA., A CAR THAT HAD VERY RECENTLY PASSED OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER LOST CONTROL ON THE ICY HIGHWAY.  AS THIS WAS HAPPENING ANOTHER TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF PASSING OUR UNIT.  THE PASSING TRACTOR TRAILER HAD NOT YET COMPLETED THE PASS, WHEN THE OUT OF CONTROL CAR STRUCK THE PASSING TRACTOR.  THE PASSING TRAILER THEN HIT OUR TRACTOR FORCING IT INTO THE DITCH AND UP A BANK.  OUR TRACTOR TRAILER CAME TO A STOP (IN THE DITCH) LAYING ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE.  OUR TRAILER LOADED WITH 800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE DID NOT LEAK.  THE LEBANON CO.  EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  H.M.H.T.T.C., OF HARRISBURG WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE, AND THEY OFF-LOADED OUR WRECKED TANKER INTO ANOTHER TANKER.  TO MY UNDERSTANDING, WHEN DRILLING THE OFF LOADING HOLE IN THE OVER TURNED TANKER, A SMALL SPILLAGE.

column168: (A) TANK CAR UTLX 042167 WAS INVOLVED IN AN ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD DERAILMENT AT CRENSHAW, MISSISSIPPI. THE TANK WAS DERAILED AND TURNED OVER ON ITS SIDE AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. A SMALL DRIP OF PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE VALVE AREA AT THE TOP OF THE CAR BUT WE WERE UNABLE TO DETERMINE WHICH CLOSURE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD, HAZ MAT TECH, MR GREG HENSHAW TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS AND SECURED ALL VALVES IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THIS SLOWED THE DRIP BUT DID NOT STOP IT. THE LEAK COMPLETELY STOPPED WHEN THE CAR WAS UP RIGHTED AND RE RAILED. THE TANK CAR WAS BADLY DAMAGED AND THE PRODUCT HAD TO BE TRANSFERRED TO UTLX 013961 FOR TRANSPORT ON THE CONSIGNEE. (B) TANK CAR UTLX 079402 WAS INVOLVED IN AN ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD DERAILMENT AT CRENSHAW, MISSISSIPPI. THIS TANK CAR WAS DERAILED AND TURNED OVER AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SHEERED OFF BUT NO LEAKS COULD BE DETECTED FROM THAT AREA. A SMALL DRIP OF PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA BUT WE WERE UNABLE TO TELL WHICH CLOSURE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, MR. GREG HENSHAW TIGHTENED ALL BOLTS AND SECURED ALL VALVES IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THIS ACTION DID SLOW THE LEAK BUT DID NOT STOP IT. THE LEAK WAS COMPLETELY STOPPED WHEN THE CAR WAS UP RIGHTED AND RERAILED. TANK CAR WAS BADLY DAMAGED AND HAD TO BE TRANSFERRED TO UTLX 078621 FOR TRANSPORT BACK TO SHIPPER. (C) TANK CAR UTLX 641537 WAS INVOLVED IN AN ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD DERAILMENT AT CRENSHAW, MISSISSIPPI, THE TANK CAR WAS DERAILED AND TURNED OVER AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS SHEERED OFF WITH A SMALL DRIP TYPE LEAK COMING FROM THE EXPOSED BALL VALVE. PRODUCT WAS RUNNING OUT OF THE MANWAY COVER AREA. ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, MR. GREG HENSHAW ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE MANWAY BOLTS AND WAS ABLE TO SLOW IT DOWN, BUT NOT ABLE TO STOP IT. column168: AB 12498F, SHIPPER: C. GRISSELLE, AWB# JNB 4413283490 SNC.  THIS IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  04:11, 12/03/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN "A" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT " ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN CHUCK JONES RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, HE FOUND A BROWN FIBREBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  AS HE APPROACHED THE BOX, HE NOTICED AN ODOR EMITTING FROM THE BOX.  HE REGRESSED AND DONNED AN AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATOR WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES.  HE RE-ENTERED IN AREA, TESTED THE LEAKING LIQUID WITH PH TEST PAPER, READING WAS NEUTRAL.  HE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX WERE VARIOUS PERSONAL, AND FOOD ITEMS INCLUDING 4-250 ML PLASTIC SPRAY PUMP BOTTLES OF HAIR SPRAY.   THE BOTTLES INDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE FLAMMABLE.  ON ONE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES, THE CLOSURE WAS BROKEN CAUSING THE ENTIRE 250 ML TO LEAK. THE LEAKING HAIR SPRAY WAS ALSO THE CAUSE OF THE ODOR.  THE REMAINING THREE BOTTLES OF HAIR SPRAY DID NOT LEAK.  NONE OF THE REMAINING ITEMS INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. HE RESEAL THE SHIPMENT, PLACED IT INSIDE TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED IT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED UNDER LOCK AND KEY INSIDE THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THE AREA INVOLVED IN THE SPILL WAS CLEANED VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED. column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING UNLOADED WHEN HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED LEAKAGE AND ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED EXAMINE TO REVEAL FIVE ONE GALLON CAPACITY METAL CANS.  THE SUBSTANCE HAD THE SMELL AND APPEARANCE OF SOME TYPE OF SOME TYPE OF LACQUER/VARNISH. THE SPILLED ITEMS WERE CONTAINED AND PUT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED.  THE INFORMATION ON THE MSDS SUGGESTS THAT THE MATERIAL MET THE DEFINITION OF A FLAMMABLE PAINT RELATED PRODUCT.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS, OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.  DIANA LAGUNA, SPECIAL AGENT, FAA/MIA/CAFSO WAS INITIALLY CONTACTED ON THIS SITUATION.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE-FUEL OIL MIXTURE (CONTAINING ONLY PRILLED AMMONIUM NITRATE AND FUEL OIL)
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON DECEMBER 2, 1998 A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON TRUCK #6150 OWNED BY WAMPUM HARDWARE CO AND OPERATOR BY KENNETH ZINK WAS INVOLVED IN AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A SMALL SPILL (1,200-1,400#) OF AMMONIUM NITRATE-FUEL OIL MIXTURE COMMONLY REFERRED TO AS AN/FO. ACCORDING TO INFORMATION SUPPLIED BY THE DRIVER (OHIO TRAFFIC WITNESS STATEMENT ATTACHED),  THE BRAKES FAILED AS THE DRIVER APPROACHED THE WEIGH SCALE LOCATED NEAR MILE POST #175.  IN A EFFORT TO AVOID HITTING OTHER VEHICLES THE DRIVER DROVE INTO THE DITCH TEARING OUT 5 FENCE POSTS, PROCEEDING TO HIT BRIDGE ABUTMENT AND ROLLING OVER A LEAST ONCE.  THE VEHICLE HAS SEVERAL COMPARTMENTS WHERE THE DIFFERENT PRODUCTS WERE BEING STORED DURING SHIPMENT. FOR CLARIFICATION PURPOSES PLEASE REFER TO THE DRAWING.  WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER A SMALL QUANTITY (ESTIMATES 1200-1400 LBS) OF AMMONIUM NITRATE-FUEL OIL MIXTURE (AN/FO) WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE TRUCK ONTO THE GROUND.  THE TRUCK WAS EQUIPPED WITH A LOCKING-BAR MECHANISM DESIGNED TO KEEP THE HATCH LIDS FROM OPENING IN THE EVENT OF A ROLLOVER.  THE ACTUAL RELEASE WAS CAUSED WHEN A CORNER OF ONE OF THE HATCHES WAS BENT DURING THE ACCIDENT ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO FLOW OUT OF THE TRUCK DURING THE ROLLOVER MOTION.  THE LOCKING BAR MECHANISM DID PREVENT THE HATCHES FROM OPENING.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP THE SAME MORNING BY A QUALIFIED CONTRACTOR (ERS OF OHIO INC, WESTON, OH).  THE PRODUCT WAS COLLECTED IN DRUMS AND RETURNED TO WAMPUM HARDWARE'S STORAGE LOCATION WHERE IT WILL BE RECYCLED AND DISPOSED OF IN A FUTURE BLAST.  THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO WAMPUM HARDWARE'S GARAGE UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE OHIO STATE PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION.  POST ACCIDENT BRAKES TESTS WERE CONDUCTED BY PUCO (KELLY HEDGLIN).  NO DEFICIENCIES WERE FOUND AND THE DRIVER WAS CITED FOR FALLING TO HAVE HIS VEHICLE UNDER CONTROL.

column168: On Friday, Dec. 4, 1998, I released rail car EAGX19048. On Monday, Dec. 7, I released rail car EAGX19001. On Tuesday, December 8, 1998, I released rail car GATX 61022. Wednesday, December 9, 1998, I called Sue to see if the rail cars had been pulled out. She said that she had given the cars to Bill Tilker. Sue said that if the cars were not pulled, to call her back. I got to Huntco Steel around 3:30 pm. The line had been down and it was about 6:00 pm when it was loaded. I arrived at the rail site around 6:30 pm and assumed that all three cars had been pulled. It was dark and there weren't any lights (which I have repeatedly asked for). The EAGX cars are brown. The GATX cars are white. I had three white GATX cars in a row. They all started with the number 61. The rail pulled two brown EAGX cars from the front. The third car was a white GATX that was also loaded. Instead of pulling the third car out they pushed it to the front with two other white GATX cars. I climbed up the rail car, opened the lid and put the hose in and strapped the hose down. I then hooked the hose to the truck, opened the valve and went to the front of the rail cars and put the blue flag up. I returned to the truck to start the air compressor. It was about 7pm. At about 7:30 pm the rail car started to run over. The pump holds the air at about 18PSI, which means that it blows off the acid at about 115 gallons a minute. It took about four minutes to shut the system down. I then checked to make sure that it didn't go into the road. I then called Harold Hinkle at his home to immediately report the spill. He said to make sure that it was contained in the smallest possible area by hauling in lime rock. I called Don Cocke and he called J.B. Gibbens. They brought lime rock and spread it on the spill to contain it. I went to the Blytheville Fire Department and reported the spill to the captain on duty. There wasn't any listing for the EPA in the Blytheville area. The fire dept. went over to the rail site and inspected the gravel containment and told me it was okay to go back to work. The fire dept. called Schererville and talked to someone at the Schererville office.

column168: CROWN VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON INTERSTATE 440, DRIVER WILLIAM MCLAMB. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:40 HOURS ON 12/18/98, CROWN VEHICLE STRUCK AN ABANDONED PICKUP TRUCK PARKED PARTIALLY IN THE TRAVEL LANES, LOCATED BETWEEN EXITS 10 AND 11. AFTER STRIKING THE PICKUP TRUCK, THE CROWN VEHICLE PROCEEDED EAST BOUND, INTO AN EMBANKMENT ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER,TURNING 180 IN THE PROCESS. THE CROWN VEHICLE THEN  FLIPPED ON ITS SIDE, AND ERUPTED IN FLAMES. BOTH VEHICLE WERE CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. THE VEHICLE WAS LOADED WITH 9100 GALLONS GASOLINE. ALL GALLONS OF GASOLINE WERE BURNT UP IN THE FIRE. THE GASOLINE /FIRE ENTERED THE STORM SEWER AND PROCEEDED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1/8 MILE FROM THE ACCIDENT SITE IN A DRAINAGE DITCH. THE FIRE IGNITED SEVERAL SMALL BRUSH FIRES IN THE AREA, WHICH WERE EXTINQUISHED. OTHER THAN THE ABANDONED PICKUP TRUCK, NO OTHER VEHICLE WERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT.

column168: ON 12/16/98 SORT SUPERVISOR, DAVE HARP REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR IN THE MAIN SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR INC.  PART TIME HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIANS, CHRIS CHAPPA AND DIANE RAMSDEN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE AFFECTED AREA WAS ISOLATED.  TECHNICIAN RAMSDEN DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. INSIDE WAS A "GALILEO THERMOMETER".  THIS IS A GLASS RECEPTACLE WITH A CAPACITY OF APPROXIMATELY OF 2 QUARTS.  THE INSERT THAT WAS SHIPPED WITH THIS STATES "INNER LIQUID SHOULD NOT COME INTO CONTACT WITH OPEN FLAME".  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY IN THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 12/18/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS ON OUR "D" RAMP IN AIRCRAFT N982AX, TAIL NUMBER, FLIGHT #155.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, TAMMY FLORENCE AND CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AND ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AS FOLLOWS:  INNER PACKAGES COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBED SPECIFICATIONS, PAINT, UN1263 AND ORIENTATION ARROWS. THE SPEC MARKINGS ARE AS FOLLOWS:  UN4G/Y38.6/S/98/USA+AA173.  A LABEL OF (FLAMMABLE LIQUID).  THE MANUFACTURE SEAL WAS AS FOLLOWS: RAYMARK CONTAINER, ATLANTA, GA, ALSO ATTACHED TO THE SHIPMENT WAS AN AIRWAY BILL AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE OUTER BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND 5 - 1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLES (CONTAINING PAINT).  THESE RECEPTACLES WERE PACKED IN 1 FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT THAT LEAKED.  THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT ENOUGH ROOM LEFT FOR OUTAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED DUE TO ODOR AND LEAKAGE AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 12/18/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.   THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL AND ODOR WAS IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, BRUCE SHILTZ AND PAUL SCHMIDT RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AND ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AS FOLLOWS:  PROPER SHIPPING NAME, THE UN NUMBER, ORIENTATION ARROWS.  THIS SIDE UP, INNER PACKAGES COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBED SPECIFICATIONS, OVER PACK CONTAINS 3 @ 2.8 L - 8.4 L TOTAL, APPROVED FOR AIR SHIPMENT.  THE MANUFACTURE SEAL (CHESAPEAKE PACKAGING, BINGHATON, NY, THE ATTACHED ITEMS WERE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PAPERWORK AND A SHEET OF PAPER WITH THE ROUTING INFORMATION.  THIS BOX CONTAINED 3 SMALLER BOXES.  THE CONTENTS OF THE SMALLER BOXES WERE AS FOLLOWS:  EACH BOX CONTAINED 1 METAL RECEPTACLE AT 2.8 LITERS EACH.  THE 3 METAL RECEPTACLES HAD SCREW TYPE CLOSURES WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  THIS IS THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR LEAKAGE.  THERE WAS AND ESTIMATED 2 OUNCES OF ISPROPANOL THAT LEAKED FROM THE CLOSURE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 12/11/98 A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVER WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "A" BUILDING SORT FACILITY, PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN, CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL SHE DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR OF PERFUME.  THE BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE:  FRAGILE, NEXT AFTERNOON SERVICE, AND OLD LABEL STATING TRIO SD1.  SPARE-O-DOOR TRAP.  THE MANUFACTURE SEAL (MILLER CONTAINER CORP).  THE REST OF THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS OBSCURED. THERE WAS ALSO AIRWAY BILL INFORMATION ON THE BOX.  THERE WERE NOT MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THIS TO CONTAIN REGULATED MATERIAL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND:  4 GLASS, PUMP SPRAY BOTTLES AT 125 MLS EACH, PACKED IN PAPER PACKING MATERIAL.  THE CONTENTS IN THE BOTTLES WAS ZERMAT EAU DE TOILETTE COLOGNE OF WHICH 1 BOTTLE WAS BROKEN AND ALL CONTENTS WERE LOST.  THE BOTTLE WAS FOUND TO BE BROKER AND THE REASON FOR THE BREAKAGE WAS THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL OF THE SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE A REGULATED MATERIAL AND WILL BE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED DUE TO ODOR AND LEAKAGE AND WILL BE HELD UNTIL COMPLETION OF THE INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

THIS PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED ON THE SORT BELT, DURING THE SORTING OPERATION.  THE BELT AREA WAS SHUT DOWN, AND EMPLOYEES WERE MOVED TO ANOTHER BELT TO PREVENT CONTACT WITH THIS SUBSTANCE. MGR AL CALDO, CONTACTED ME REGARDING THE INCIDENT AND I ADVISED HIM WE NEEDED TO CONTACT THE FEDEX ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST TO MAKE CONTACT WITH A LOCAL OFFICE THAT COULD HANDLE THIS TYPE OF ENVIRONMENTAL SUBSTANCE SPILL.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX THAT THIS SUBSTANCE LEAKED FROM,  WAS NOT LABELED, MARKED, OR DECLARED AS CONTAINING ANY DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCTS.  APPARENTLY ONE, OR SEVERAL PLASTIC VIALS WERE BROKEN AND THE SUBSTANCE LEAKED FROM THE PLASTIC BAGGIES THAT HELD THE VIALS.  I ADVISED AL, TO ISOLATE THE BOX AND TO LIMIT HIS EXPOSURE.  THE OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AND HANDLED THE SPILL CLEANUP, SO SOME OF THE SPECIFIC INNER CONTAINER INFORMATION IS NOT KNOWN.  THE FAA EASTERN REGION DUTY OFFICE WAS CONTACTED TO REPORT THIS INCIDENT.  I LATER FOLLOWED UP WITH JOE BALLAS OF THE EWR/CASFO.  THE PACKAGE AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WERE LEFT IN SALVAGE DRUMS SO THAT THE FAA COULD BEGIN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  CONTENTS OF THIS INCIDENT WERE TO BE DISPOSED OF BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL VENDOR THAT HANDLED THE SPILL CLEANUP.

I RECEIVED A CALL FROM A FEDEX DG SPECIALIST REPORTING THAT A MANAGER HAD TAKEN A DG PACKAGE, A 1.4S EXPLOSIVE OFF THE BELT AND IT WAS VIBRATING. I INSTRUCTED THEM TO ENSURE EMPLOYEES WERE A MINIMUM OF 20' AWAY FROM THE FREIGHT.  IT HAD ALREADY BEEN PLACED ON THE FLOOR OF THE WAREHOUSE ON A CONCRETE FLOOR AWAY FROM THE BELT AND OTHER EMPLOYEES.  CONES HAD BEEN PLACED AROUND THE PACKAGE AND EMPLOYEES IN THE AREA HAD BEEN INSTRUCTED NOT TO GO NEAR THE PACKAGE. I THEN PHONED THE SHIPPER TO SEE IF THEY COULD PROVIDE ME WITH ANY ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ABOUT THE SHIPMENT. I WAS TOLD CONTENTS LOOK LIKE BULLETS AND THERE WAS NOTHING ELSE INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  I HAD ASKED THAT IN CASE THERE MIGHT BE SOMETHING ELSE REACTING WITH THE EXPLOSIVE.  I CONTACTED THE RECIPIENT COMPANY BUT WAS TOLD THE PURCHASING MANAGER THAT MIGHT KNOW SOMETHING ABOUT THE PACKAGE WAS NOT THERE AT THE TIME.  I CALLED THE MANUFACTURER AND SPOKE WITH BOTH THE TECHNICAL MANAGER AND THE PRODUCTS SUPPORT MANAGER.  I ASKED WHAT WOULD HAPPEN IF SOMETHING WENT WRONG WITH THE PACKAGE AND WAS TOLD IT WOULD EXPLODE THEN CATCH FIRE.  I ASKED IF THEY HAD EVER HAD A PARTIAL RELEASE WHICH WOULD CAUSE CONTINUOUS VIBRATION AND THEY SAID NO.  I SPOKE AGAIN WITH THE FEDEX DG PERSONNEL, THIS TIME WITH THE DG COORDINATOR.  HE SAID THE PACKAGE WAS STILL VIBRATING.  AS APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES HAD GONE BY BETWEEN WHEN THE MANAGER SAW THE VIBRATION AND REMOVED IT FROM THE BELT AND THE DG COORDINATOR SAW IT VIBRATING ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR, I MADE THE DECISION TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING COMPLETELY.  I INSTRUCTED THE FEDEX SR MGR TO EVACUATE AND CALL THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT SO THEIR HAZMAT TEAM COULD INVESTIGATE.  I NOTIFIED FAA AGENT JOE CLARK WHO WENT OVER IMMEDIATELY.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND PORT AUTHORITY BOTH RESPONDED, IT HAD STOPPED VIBRATING AND THEY FOUND NOTHING OUT OF THE ORDINARY INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  DRUMMED FOR DISPOSITION.

This shipment was found to be leaking in our system. Upon inspection of the contents during spill cleanup procedures several items were found inside. These included:(a) sealer and shellac a metal container (b)artist adhesive spray in an aerosol can (c) dentured alcohol solvents (d) acrylic paint in plastic tubes, this said corrosive on it (d) paper cement in a glass bottle, this one said flammable. Item A is believed to be Paint, UN 1263. Item B is believed to be Aerosols, non-flammable, n.o.s. Item C is believed to be Paint related material, UN 3166. Item D is believed to be Paint, UN 1266. Item E is believed to be Adhesive , UN 1166. Spilled material from this package spilled on an employees hands and he experienced a burning sensation but washed it off and was all right. Proper spill cleanup procedures occurred and the package was held in a salvage drum pending F.A.A investigation. As the package was not sent with a shipper's declaration, and had no dg markings or labeling, it is believed to be undeclared dangerous goods. F.A.A. agent Gary Shandling was notified.

As the package was not sent with a shipper's declaration, and had no dg markings or labeling, it is believed to be undeclared dangerous goods. F.A.A. agent Gary Shandling was notified.

column25: A P L LAND TRANSPORT SERV
column168: Manager CTS R. Sloane was notified by RMCC of a leaking container at the UP Seattle Intermodal Facility. The container was loaded with various Acidic and Basic cleaning solutions identified as corrosive liquid or solid nos and flammable liquid nos. Upon arrival Mr. Sloane conducted tests and sampling and determined the spilled material to be a corrosive solution with a PH of 2. After opening the container it was discover that a 275 gallon "tote" had suffered a crack in the package material that resulted in the release of approximately 20 gallons of material. The material was a concrete cleaner with hydrochloric acid in the solution. A contractor, Foss environmental, was called to assist with the clean up. The plastic tote was patched and the container cleaned and forwarded to the consignee for unloading.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: Notified by RMCC 1140, of  leaking tank car DUPX 26560, at Angleton, TX. EMG Manager, Don Jenks arrived at 1:30 pm and found car overloaded. He called Dupont at Bloomington Plant and requested assistance. DuPont advised that Dow would respond for DuPont and handle transfer of some product to a tank truck. Car was leaking from relief valve from the time Mgr Jenks arrived until 5pm. PRessure in tank car was 156psi and relief valve was set at 150 psi. Transfer completed by 6pm. Leaking material limited to area under tank car as car had not been moved after arrival. Garner Environmental handled environmental clean up the following day. Vergil Perry of Garner supervised transfer and clean up. Contaminated ballast and dirt from under track was disposed of by Garner Environmental under Dupont's supervision.

Dennis Johnson, Manager, CTS was notified of the above car leaking. Investigation revealed that the bottom outlet valve was not properly secured. Valve was closed and secured in the closed position and car allowed to continue in transportation.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: Dennis Johnson, Mgr, CTS was notified of a leaking container at the intermodal ramp in Long Beach, CA. Investigation revealed that three drums were leaking and 11 others had to be placed in overpacks for a total of 14 drums. It appears that the drums were loaded loose in the container, which caused rubbing and consequently leakage. The fourteen drums were shipped back to the manufacturer and the rest of the load was released for transportation.

Dennis Johnson, Mgr CTS was notified of Tank Car IAPX on track 38 in the Colton departure yards leaking liquid and not merely venting. Investigation by the shipper revealed that the packing gland on the liquid line had come loose in transportation. The packing gland was replaced on the liquid line valve and the car released for transportation.

While unloading his trailer with his pick ups on it the driver noticed that there was some leakage around the top of the drum. He called John Downs to check it out. Mr. Downs called the HM Hotline, OEP local service center manager, Rodney Myers and Conway's regional safety supervisor Lynn Newsome. Followed the instructions given by regional safety supervisor on cleaning up and did so. Called HM Release Hotline to inform them that the haz mat was contained.
Airbound tank and petrometer malfunctioned.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: MR. LARSON (CUSTOMER) OFFERED 2 BAGS (ONE A PLASTIC CASE) FOR CHECK-IN ON FLIGHT 723 FROM ORLANDO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (MCO) TO NASHVILLE INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (BNA). SHARON VOSS, SOUTHWEST AIRLINES CUSTOMER SERVICE AGENT, QUESTIONED MR. LARSON ABOUT THE CONTENTS OF THE PLASTIC CASE AND WAS INFORMED THAT THE CASE CONTAINED "TOOLS" MR. LARSON ABOUT THE CONTENTS OF THE PLASTIC CASE AND WAS INFORMED THAT THE CASE CONTAINED "TOOL". MR. LARSON DID NOT INDICATE AT ANY POINT THAT THE CASE CONTAINED A CHAIN SAW FILLED WITH GASOLINE. BASED ON THIS EXPLANATION. SHARON ACCEPTED THE BAGGAGE AND CHECKED IT FOR BNA. THE CASE MISSED THE FLIGHT AND WAS SHIPPED TO BNA ON THE NEXFLIGHT (FLIGHT #1409) UNDER AN EXPEDITE TAG. UPON ARRIVAL IN BNA, BAGGAGE SERVICE AGENTS NOTICED A GASOLINE ODOR AND INSPECTED THE CASE FOR IT'S CONTENTS. THE CASE WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN A CHAIN SAW WHICH HAD LEAKED OIL AND GASOLINE. BAGGAGE SERVICE  PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THEIR MANAGER, WHO INFORMED SOUTHWEST AIRLINES SAFETY DEPARTMENT. THE INCIDENT WAS THEN IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO THE FAA. THE INITIAL REPORT WAS PROVIDED TO THE FAA. THE INITIAL REPORT WAS PROVIDED TO THE FAA SOUTHERN REGION OPERATIONS CENTER DUE TO THE TIME OF DAY AND THE FACT THAT IT WAS THE HOLIDAY SEASON. A FOLLOW UP WAS MADE WITH THE NASHVILLE CASFO THE FOLLOWING DAY. ALL MCO PERSONNEL INVOLVED WITH THE ACCEPTANCE AND HANDLING OF THE CHAIN SAW HAVE BEEN DISCIPLINED WITH A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION. ADDITIONALLY, THEY WILL BE INVOLVED WITH RECURRENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRAINING AT THE STATION FOR 1999. MIKE MILLER, MCO STATION MANAGER, HAS ISSUED A MEMORANDUM TO ALL MCO STATION PERSONNEL TO BE WATCHFUL FOR HIDDEN SHIPMENTS DURING THE ACCEPTANCE AND LOADING PROCESS.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, TIM HINES AND JEFF KIDDER RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND THE FOLLOWING:  A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING A FUEL ODOR AND SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX.  THE MARKINGS AND LABELS WERE: PROPER SHIPPING NAME, UN# THE WORDS (THIS SIDE UP), ORIENTATION ARROWS, THE SPEC MARKINGS: UN4G/YS/S/97/USA M4496.  THE MANUFACTURE SEAL WAS REGAL CORRUGATED BOX CO., PHILADELPHIA, PA.  THE LABEL WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL.  THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WAS ATTACHED TO THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THIS BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THEY DISCOVERED TWO FUEL FILTERS EACH WAS IN A PLASTIC BAG.  THE INSPECTION OF THE PLASTIC BAG FOUND THEM NOT TO BE SEALED PROPERLY AND APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES HAD LEAKED FROM EACH FILTER.  ABSORBENT WAS NOT FOUND INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM DUE TO THE ODOR AND LEAKAGE AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

column42: VEHICLE, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED OR VEHICLE, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED
column168: AB 13498 DOT, SHPR : WJPX -T6 CHANNEL 24, AIRWAY BILL SJU 82585286 PBI. THIS IS AN UNCLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT. ON 12/24/98 A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS INOUR "K" BUILDING SORT FACILITY. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNA RESOR AND CHARLES JONES RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A SPILL WITH AN ODOR OF GASOLINE. UPON INSPECTION  THEY DISCOVERED 3 BOXES MARKED "JAPAN"  " GENERATOR" "GROUPELECTROGENE "AND THE MANUFACTURE"S MARKINGS FOR THE PRODUCT. THERE WAS ALSO AN AIRWAY BILL LABEL. THERE WERE NO OTHER  MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THESE BOXES TO CONTAIN REGULATED MATERIAL. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: EACH BOX CONTAINED METAL & PLASTIC GAS POWERED GENERATORS( HONDA EB 2500). TWO OF THE THREE GENERATORS WERE LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR. TWO OF THE GENERATORS LEAKED 2 OUNCES EACH. IT WAS BELIEVED THAT THE THREE GENERATORS CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES EACH OF GASOLINE. THE SPILL WAS COMMING FROM THE GAS LINES OF THE GENERATOR. THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY UNSECURED LINES. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45 PM ON DECEMBER 30, 1998 CENEX HARVEST STATES (CHS) EMPLOYEE BILL MATHEWS PARKED HIS PROPANE GAS DELIVERY VEHICLE NEXT TO A LOADING RISER AT THE CHS DES  MOINES, IA PROPANE GAS PLANT LOCATED AT 4509 NE 14TH STREET. HE LEFT HIS VEHICLE TO MAKE A PHONE CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT FOR MAINTENANCE ON THE MALFUNCTIONING ENGINE. ANOTHER CHS DRIVER, TODD CARLSON, WHILE LOADING HIS  VEHICLE AT AN ADJACENT RISER AND BELIEVING THAT MATHEWS'  VEHICLE        WAS TO BE LOADED, BEGAN LOADING MATHEWS' DELIVERY VEHICLE. A SHORT TIME LATER, MATHEWS RETURNED; NOT REALIZING THAT  CARLSON WAS LOADING HIS VEHICLE, BEGAN TO PULL AWAY. CARLSON REALIZING WHAT WAS ABOUT TO HAPPEN SCREAMED AND SIGNALED FOR MATHEWS TO STOP. MATHEWS, NOT UNDERSTANDING THE SHOUTED WARNING OR THE HAND SIGNALS, CONTINUED TO PULL AHEAD AT WHICH POINT THE CONNECTED HOSE BROKE. MATHEWS TRAVEL WAS A DISTANCE ESTIMATED TO BE 3 FEET. THE BROKEN HOSE DISCHARGED PROPANE GAS (C3H8) WHICH MAY HAVE BEEN INGITED BY THE VEHICLE ENGINE. BOTH DELIVERY TRUCKS AS WELL AS ADJACENT  CYLINDER DELIVERY WERE ENGULFED IN FLAMES. LES WILLIAMS, A CHS EMPLOYEE, IN THE AREA AT THE TIME OF INCIDENT, RACED TO THE 30,000 GALLON PROPANE STORAGE VESSEL FEEDING THE FIRE AND TURNED OFF THE LIQUID VALVE WITHIN  MINUTES LIMITING THE LOSS OF PROPANE GAS FROM THE STORAGE VESSEL TO APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS.SIMULTANEOUSLY BILL MATHEWS RACED TO A PHONE LOCATED IN A CYLINDER FILL-SHED LOCATED 20 YARDS NORTH OF THE RISERS AND NOTIFIED THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL VIA 911. UPON ARRIVAL LOCAL  FIRE AND HAZ-MAT AUTHORITIES REQUESTED THAT ALL PLANT PERSONNEL EVACUATE THE AREA. SELECTED PLANT MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL WERE ASKED TO JOIN THE AUTHORITIES AT A COMMAND CENTER ESTABLISHED AT A NEAR-BY FIRE STATION. THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ASKED NEAR-BY RESIDENTS AND AREA BUSINESSES TO EVACUATE. FIRE AUTHORITIES ALLOWED THE DELIVERY UNIT TO BURN RATHER THAN PUTTING INDIVIDUALS AT UNNECESSARY RISK BY EXTINGUISHING THE FIRE. WHEN THE BULK PROPANE GAS DELIVERY UNITS FINISHED BURNING THE FIRE AUTHORITIES APPLIED WATER TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE ON THE CYLINDER DELIVERY VEHICLE AND CLOSED THE VAPOR RETURN LINES  ON THE 30,000 GALLON STORAGE VESSEL ENDING THE EMERGENCY AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 PM.  THE INCIDENT RESULTED TO DAMAGE TO THE THREE DELIVERY TRUCKS, TWO FILL HOSES, TWO VAPOR RETURN LINES, AND WIRING TO AN EXPLOSION-PROOF LIGHT IN THE AREA. THERE WAS SMOKE FROM THE AFFECTED DELIVERY VEHICLES AND THE BURNING OF AN ESTIMATED 450 GALLONS OF PROPANE GAS IN THE ATMOSPHERE ORIGINATING FROM THE DELIVERY VEHICLES. IMMEDIATE ACTIONS BY PLANT PERSONNEL LIMITED THE EXPOSURE AND RISK TO THE BURNING OF APPROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS OF PROPANE. UNFORTUNATELY THE CHAOTIC CONDITION AT THE FACILITY FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT RESULTED IN OUR LESS THAN TIMELY COMMUNICATION. IMMEDIATE FOLLOW-UP AT THIS FACILITY AND OTHER CHS FACILITIES IS BEING CONDUCTED TO HEIGHTEN AWARENESS OF SAFETY PROCEDURES AND PRACTICES.MORE STRINGENT GUIDELINES AND REQ

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: A WHEELCHAIR WITH TWO WET CELL BATTERIES WAS LOADED ABOARD SOUTHWEST FLIGHT 1881 FROM CHICAGO MIDWAY AIRPORT (MDW) BOUND TO ORLANDO INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT (MCO). UPON ARRIVAL AT MCO, BAGGAGE SERVICE PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THE INCIDENT AND CONTACTED THEIR SUPERVISORS AND MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL TO DECONTAMINATE AND INSPECT THE AIRCRAFT. SOUTHWEST NOTIFIED THE CASFO VIA THE FAA SOUTHERN REGION OPERATIONS CENTER SINCE IT WAS LATE IN THE EVENING AND A HOLIDAY SCHEDULE. INTERNAL INVESTIGATIONS INDICATE THAT A MISCOMMUNICATION OCCURRED BETWEEN A SOUTHWEST OPERATIONS AGENT (SCOTT HABERKAMP) AND THE RAMP AGENT (ERIC COLEMAN) WHO LEADED THE PIECE OF EQUIPMENT. THE FATHER OF THE CHILD IN THE WHEELCHAIR ADVISED SCOTT THAT THE CHAIR HAD BEEN "BROKEN DOWN" BOTH AGENTS HAVE RECEIVED A FINAL LETTER OF WARNING AND ASSUME RESPONSIBILITY FOR THEIR ACTIONS. EACH EMPLOYEES HAS BEEN COUNSELED IN THEIR RESPONSIBILITIES REGARDING THE PROPER ACCEPTANCE, INSPECTION, NOTIFICATION, PACKAGING AND TRANSPORTATION OF WHEELCHAIR BATTERIES. THEY HAVE ALSO BEEN ADVISED OF THE CONSEQUENCES OF THEIR ACTIONS FELT BY OUR CUSTOMER AND CUSTOMER'S FAMILY.MDW EMPLOYEES HAVE RECEIVED A LETTER EMPHASIZING THE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING THE PROPER PROCEDURES AND ARE RETRAINED IN THE WHEELCHAIR PROCEDURES AS THEY COMPLETE THE 1999 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROGRAM.

MERCURY SPILL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE BAGGAGE HOLD AREA OF A BOEING 757. ON DECEMBER 24, 1998 OUR MAINTENANCE CREW WAS PERFORMING A ROUTINE INSPECTION ON AIRCRAFT N519AT IN THE RAMP AT IND AND SPOTTED A FEW DROPS OF MERCURY ON THE FLOOR OF THE C-2 BAGGAGE COMPARTMENT. MORE MERCURY WAS FOUND TO HAVE SEEPED THROUGH THE FLOOR PANELS INTO THE AREA BELOW. SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA WAS CALLED FOR CLEANUP AND PROPER HANDLING OF 12 FLUID OZ. OF MERCURY. THREE (3) EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO THE CLINIC AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLEANED AND TREATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH BOEING MAINTENANCE MANUAL 05-51-21. FINAL DISPOSAL OF THE MERCURY IS BEING COORDINATED WITH ENVIROSOLV. THERE IS NO KNOWN SHIPMENT OF MERCURY MATERIAL. IT COULD HAVE FROM FROM A PASSENGER BAG ON A COMMERCIAL FLIGHT OR A PASSENGER BAG ON A MILITARY FLIGHT. IN CHECKING THE FLIGHT MANIFESTS, WE SHOW NO EVIDENCE OF ANY SHIPMENTS ON RECENT FLIGHTS. FURTHER, THE INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH SEVERAL PERSONS RESPONSIBLE FOR CONTRACTING AND COORDINATING THE MILITARY FLIGHTS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL REPRESENTATIVE FOR AMC, SCOTT AFB. NONE OF THESE INDIVIDUALS HAVE ANY AWARENESS OR RECORDS OF ANY SHIPMENTS. THE FLIGHT ALL APPEAR TO BE COMPRISED OF ONLY PASSENGERS AND THEIR BAGS.

column168: UNIT #1 WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON US 127 BYPASS. THE ROAD WAS WET, WITH SOME DRY SPOTS. AS THE LIGHT CHANGED TO CAUTION, THE OPERATOR OF UNIT #1 APPLIED HIS BRAKES, WHICH LOCKED ON THE WET SURFACE. UNIT #1 SKIDDED THROUGH THE RED LIGHT. UNIT #2 PROCEEDED EAST ON US 68, THROUGH A GREEN LIGHT, AND THE VEHICLES COLLIDED IN THE INTERSECTION. UNIT #1 OVERTURNED AFTER IMPACT. UNIT #1 WAS LOADED WITH 8,500 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THE DRIVER OF UNIT #1 WAS NOT INJURED. THE DRIVER OF UNIT #2 WAS PRONOUNCED DEAD AT THE HAGGIN HOSPITAL IN MERCER CO. UPON IMPACT WITH THE ROAD SURFACE THE TANKER RUPTURED ON THE RIGHT SIDE SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 2,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. LEWIS TRANSPORT, INC. WAS NOTIFIED AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES (N.R.C., KY E.P.A.,FEDERAL E.P.A., INSURANCE COMPANY). ALREADY ON SCENE WERE THE KY STATE POLICE, STATE FIRE MARSHAL'S OFFICE, MIKE MCCURRY (LEWIS BROKER WITH LEWIS EMERGENCY SPILL EQUIPMENT) AND THE MERCER CO. EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT OFFICE. ON 12/30/98 2,250 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS DELIVERED TO KOCOLENE, DANVILLE, KY, KY-ORIGINAL DESTINATION. ON 1/06/99 GASOLINE AND FOAM CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS TAKEN TO BFI WASTE SYSTEMS, BENSON VALLEY AREA LANDFILL, FRANKFORT, KY. ON 1/07/99 2,440.5 GALLONS OF CONTAMINATED GASOLINE WAS TAKEN TO SOMERSET REFINERY, SOMERSET, KY. A WATER AND FOAM MIXTURE WITH MINIMAL GASOLINE IS AT OUR LOUISVILLE, KY TERMINAL, ON A LEWIS TANKER, WAITING TO BE TAKEN TO A DISPOSAL SITE. WE'RE IN THE PROCESS OF FINDING A FACILITY THAT WILL ACCEPT THE MIXTURE. (HAZ. WASTE BILLS ATTACHED)

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Abrasion
column168: ON 12/18/98 THE OMAHA INTERMODAL RAMP REPORTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM INTERMODAL CONTAINER NOSU 423422.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CTS, AND KEN DECHANT, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT RESPONDED. A KANSAS CITY CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, INC., RESPONDED TO ASSIST IN UNLOADING THE CONTAINER TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  NINE DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED TO HAVE LOOSE BUNGS OR MISSING GASKETS.  TRACES OF PRODUCT COULD BE SEEN ON TOP OF THESE NINE DRUMS.  ONE OF THE NINE DRUMS HAD A HOLE ABRADED IN THE TOP SIDE OF THE DRUM BY AN ADJACENT DRUM DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  AFTER OVER PACKING ALL NINE DRUMS AND TRANSLOADING THE ENTIRE LOAD INTO A SECOND CONTAINER, THE LOAD WAS RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.
DURING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, A MINOR ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE MANWAY BOLTS.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, SECURING THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

column42: BUTYLENE SEE ALSO PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED
column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WHILE RESPONDING TO A REPORT OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT DEXTER, MO., WAS ADVISED THAT A BUTYLENE CAR HAD BEEN  NOTED TO BE LEAKING ON TRAIN # MNLAS07.  MANAGER TUFTS REQUESTED THAT THE TRAIN BE STOPPED AT THE NEAREST SIDING AND HE WOULD INSPECT TO DETERMINE IF LEAKAGE PRESENT.  MANAGER TUFTS NOTIFIED THE RISK MANAGEMENT DISPATCHER AND PROCEEDED TO RANDLES, MO., TO INSPECT THE TRAIN.  UPON ARRIVAL, MANAGER TUFTS NOTED A VAPOR LEAK FROM TANK CAR GATX 55593 DUE TO LIQUID VALVE PLUG THAT WAS NOT SECURE.  MANAGER TUFTS DETERMINED UPON FURTHER INSPECTION THE VALVE WAS ACTUALLY CLOSED AND THAT PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING TO THE PLUG THRU THE VALVE SEATS.  MANAGER TUFTS CONTACTED REGIONAL MANAGER HERBY BART TO DISCUSS OPTIONS FOR MITIGATION AND ALSO CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  FOLLOWING DISCUSSIONS, IT WAS DECIDED TO ATTEMPT TO REMOVE AND RETAPE AND SECURE THE VALVE PLUG.  PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE APPROXIMATELY 32 PSI AND THE PLUG WAS SLOWLY REMOVED WHICH CAUSED THE VALVE TO FORM ICE AND SPLINT THE LEAK TEMPORARILY WHILE REPAIRS WERE MADE.  MANAGER TUFTS RETAPE THE PLUG AND PLACED THE PLUG IN  POSITION, TIGHTENED IT DOWN WHICH CONTAINED THE ESCAPING VAPOR.  MANAGER TUFTS TESTED THE VALVE CLOSERS WITH SNOOP TO INSURE THAT THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND RELEASED THE CAR TO DESTINATION.  HE ADVISED THE SHIPPER THAT THE VALVE ITSELF NEEDED MECHANICAL REPAIRS OR REPLACEMENT AFTER UNLOADING THE CAR.  STATE OF MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS NOTIFIED AND ISSUED REPORT #981207-1425-LJL.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER THAT WAS PLACARDED TOXIC.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE E805 ROADWAY, AND LOCATED ABOVE 20 FOOT CONTAINER IN STALL #212.  A SMALL POOL (LESS THAN ONE GALLON) OF LIQUID WAS ON THE GROUND DIRECTLY BELOW THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER.  WHILE THE LIQUID ON THE GROUND WAS DAMP, THERE WAS NO ACTIVE LEAK AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION.  ABSORBENT WAS PLACED OVER THE SPILL AREA, AND THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS SECURED TO THROUGH TRAFFIC, EFFECTIVELY ISOLATING THE CONTAINER.  SINCE THE PRODUCT APPEARED TO HAVE COME FROM THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, A DIAPER WAS PLACED ACROSS THE REAR PORTION OF THE CONTAINER IN ORDER TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN MOVED TO THE NORTH END CONTAINMENT AREA , WHICH HAD BEEN PREPARED WITH PLASTIC SHEETING TO CONTAIN THE ENTIRE UNIT ONCE PLACED.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PRODUCT BEGAN LEAKING DURING THE MOVEMENT TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA, AND THE DIAPER EFFECTIVELY CONTAINED THE RUNOFF. ONCE THE AREA WAS ISOLATED, THE TEAM MADE ENTRY BY OPENING THE REAR DOORS.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON METAL DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, AND SECURED WITH GOOD BLOCKING AND BRACING IN ACCORDANCE WITH BOW PAMPHLE 6C.  A SMALL TRAIL OF PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED ON THE RIGHT CONTAINER SIDE WALL.  UPON REMOVING THE BLOCKING AND BRACING, REMOVAL OF THE DRUMS COMMENCED IN AN EFFORT TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  DURING THE REMOVAL OF THE ROW OF DRUMS AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER, ONE DRUM FROM THE FLOOR TIER, AGAINST THE RIGHT SIDE WALL OF THE CONTAINER, WAS NOTED LEAKING.  IT APPEARS THE DRUM HAD STRUCK THE CORRUGATED SIDE WALL OF THE CONTAINER DURING LOADING, AS THE BOTTOM CHIME HAD A 5 TO 6 INCH DEFLECTION THAT WAS CONSISTENT WITH THE SIDEWALL.  THE IRREGULAR SHAPE OF THE OUTWARD PORTION OF THE CHIME HAD FATIGUED THE INSIDE PORTION OF THE CHIME, WHERE A 3 INCH LONG CRACK DEVELOPED, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO WEEP.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED IN AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT.  BASED UPON THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM, IT APPEARED THAT ONLY 3-5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED.  THE CONTAINER AREAS AFFECTED BY THE PRODUCT WERE DECONNED PER THE MANUFACTURERS RECOMMENDATION, AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE RELOADED IN THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS HELD OUT PENDING SHIPPING INSTRUCTIONS FOR RETURN TO THE MANUFACTURER.  THE PARKING STALL WAS ALSO DECONNED AND RETURNED TO NORMAL USAGE.  BASED UPON THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER THAT WAS PLACARDED TOXIC.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF FACILITY AND LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN WEST ROADWAY (WHITE) 805 SECTION, STALL NUMBER 92.  A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE GALLON) WAS OBSERVED ON THE PAVEMENT DIRECTLY BELOW THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH HAD LEAKED THROUGH THE REAR DOOR GASKETS. ABSORBENT WAS PLACED OVER THE GROUND AREA, AND THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT FROM ESCAPING WHILE THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  ONCE THE ENTRY TEAM WAS IN PLACE, THE DOORS WERE OPENED.  THREE BULL BOARDS WERE ACROSS THE REAR OF THE LADING, WITH PLYWOOD SHEETING BETWEEN THE 5 GALLON PAILS AND THE BULL BOARDS.  UPON REMOVING THE BLOCKING AND BRACING, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE REAR LADING CONSISTED OF 5 GALLON PAILS, HAND STACKED FOUR TO FIVE HIGH.  THE PAILS WERE OFF SET ON PALLETS TO STAGGER THE LOADING PATTERN, HOWEVER, THEY WERE NOT SECURED IN ANY FASHION TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.  THE PALLETS UPON WHICH THE PAILS WERE STACKED APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED AS THERE WERE SEVERAL AREAS WHERE SCRAP BOARDS WERE USED TO SHORE UP THE TOP SLATS OF THE PALLET.  THE WEIGHT OF THE PAILS HAD CAUSED THE TOP CROSS SLATS TO SAG, AND THE SCRAP LUMBER WAS USED TO PREVENT THE PALLET FROM COLLAPSING. OVERALL, THIS IS NOT THE RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PER THE THE BOE PAMPHLET 6C.  UPON REMOVING THE PAILS, FOUR WERE FOUND TO HAVE BEEN CRUSHED AND DAMAGED, WHICH ALLOWED THEM TO LEAK A PORTION OF THEIR CONTENTS.  THE PRODUCT WAS IDENTIFIED AT BIOBAN P-1487.  AN ADDITIONAL 24 PAILS WERE FOUND TO HAVE DAMAGE THAT DEEMED THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  FURTHER INTO THE LOAD, THE LADING CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON DRUMS WHICH WERE INTACT AND SHOWED NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THE METHOD IN WHICH DRUMS WERE LOADED AND SEPARATED REQUIRED REWORKING THE LADING IN ORDER TO CONFORM TO PROPER LOADING PROTOCOLS FOR MIXED POLY AND METAL DRUMS.  THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS DECONNED PER THE MANUFACTURERS SPECIFICATIONS, THE REMAINING DRUMS AND PAILS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE HELD OUT PENDING SHIPPING INFORMATION FOR RETURN TO THE MANUFACTURER.  THE PARKING STALL WAS ALSO DECONNED AND RETURNED TO NORMAL USAGE.  DUE TO THE AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  SUPERVISOR VALDEZ STATED THE WEST END SWITCH JOB NOTED SOME MOISTURE ON THE TOP CENTER PORTION OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  SINCE THE TANK CAR WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE. IT WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD, AND UPON INSPECTING THE TOP AREA OF THE CAR, FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LIQUID TO BE COMING FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE AIR AND LIQUID LINES.  A RUSTED CABLE SEAL SECURING THE KEEPER PIN WAS CUT AWAY AND WHEN THE PROTECTIVE COVER WAS OPENED, OBSERVED THE BALL VALVE FOR THE LIQUID LINE TO BE LAYING LOOSE INSIDE THE COMPARTMENT.  A RAG HAD BEEN STUFFED INTO THE LIQUID LINE OPENING, PRESUMED TO BE SOME FORM OF A PLUG TO PREVENT LIQUID FROM ESCAPING.  CLOSER INSPECTION NOTED THE FOUR MOUNTING FLANGE BOLTS WERE SEVERELY WORN, AND TWO COULD BE TURNED BY HAND.  IT APPEARED THAT SOMEONE HAD STARTED TO REPLACE THE FLANGE BOLTS AND DID NOT COMPLETE THE WORK.  ALL FOUR OF THE FLANGE BOLTS WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED PRIOR TO REINSTALLING THE BALL VALVE, WHICH WOULD ALSO REQUIRE A NEW GASKET AND NEW FLANGE NUTS.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER, PACIFIC RESOURCE RECOVERY, AND THE NECESSARY REPAIRS DISCUSSED.  PACIFIC RESOURCE CONTACTED THE LOCAL GATX CAR REPAIR FACILITY, HOWEVER, THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO PROVIDE THE ASSISTANCE NEEDED.  PACIFIC THEN CONTACTED THE TANK CAR LEASING COMPANY AND OBTAINED INFORMATION ON THE PARTS REQUIRED TO REPAIR THE CAR.  PACIFIC THEN ARRANGED TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  ONCE THE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED, THE CAR WAS REINSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED, AT WHICH TIME IT WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE TYPE OF PRODUCT AND MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RON ELDRIDGE, CAR FOREMAN, COLTON YARD ONE SPOT CAR REPAIR FACILITY,  REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  MR. ELDRIDGE STATED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS SET TO THE ONE SPOT FOR SOME WELDING REPAIRS TO THE "B" END SAFETY APPLIANCES, AND AS A NORMAL COURSE OF INSPECTION, THE TOP PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS PROBED WITH A COMBUSTIBLE GAS DETECTOR.  THE GAS DETECTOR ALARMED INDICATING THERE WERE VAPOR LEVELS ABOVE THE LEL FOR BUTANE.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  INITIAL INSPECTION OF THE PROACTIVE HOUSING NOTED NO ODORS OR ANY INDICATIONS OF ESCAPING VAPORS.  AN AIM PROBE FOR FLAMMABLE GAS VAPOR WAS USED TO INSPECT EACH VALVE AND WHEN IT WAS PLACED INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, THE UNIT ALARMED.  A GAUGE WAS PLACED ON THE CAR AND THE INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS NOTED TO BE ONLY 60 POUNDS.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE SETTING FOR THIS CAR IS APPROXIMATELY 300 POUNDS TO DISCHARGE, INDICATING A FAULTY "O" RING.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER, ARCO, WAS ADVISED OF THE LEAK.  ARCO MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE REPAIRED PRIOR TO THE WELDING WORK BEING STARTED BY THE ONE SPOT FORCES.  DUE TO THE TYPE AND AMOUNT OF THE LEAK, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

USING DECISION TREE ALONG WITH THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND ABSORB WITH SPEEDY DRI. AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP. SCBA WAS NOT USE DUE TO THE LACK OF AN IRRITATION  ODOR AND AREA VENTILATION. ALL CANS SENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION.
